project_detail:
Works that need doing:

Installing 6 beams and removing party walls. Installing beams high up so roof is flat. (Please factor in underpinning if required)

Breaking partition wall with cupboards in empty property ground floor.

Install skirting boards first floor to join properties and ground floor where needed after works are completed. Save skirting from main property to use in hall way before walls are broken.

When the hallway is merged you will need to reconstruct a bedroom in the empty property as the hallway will affect it (cut through it) will no longer be a square room please check plans.

Join electric for 2 properties.   Includes connecting consumer units from main property to the empty property alongside providing certification it will require some rewiring. 

Join gas for 2 properties. Join all radiator pipes and water pipes to boiler in main property alongside providing certification. 

Remove boiler from empty property and cap off piping by making it neat (no piping exposed above ground).

Join water for 2 properties. Making them 1 connection.

Moving 5 radiators/replacing them.

Installing lights downstairs/ walls and upstairs. Installing new and replacing existing plug sockets for all hall ways and ground floor. (Adjust and connect light connections so it can be powered from both sides) 

Install plug sockets on first floor bathroom/ utility room in main property.

Install integrated fire alarms ground floor and first floor. 

Plastering, rendering, skimming full walls and full ceilings. 

Making partition to block dust in main property.

Remove and reposition bathroom door frame and door for bathroom on first floor. Adjust soil pipe for bathroom so roof is flat on ground floor.

Remove shower and tiles for the hallway entrance (main property). In the empty house remove shower, toilet and sink. 

Remove kitchen units etc in empty property inorder to take down the wall.

Builder will use their own tools and aids to complete works. Skips will be supplied by me upon request and materials.
summary: House / Height: 2 storeys / Type: Merging 2 properties together/steel beam work / Starting: In the next few weeks

project_detail:
We are currently looking to convert the garage in my mother in laws 2 bedroom bungalow, into an on suite bedroom, with possibly a small utility room. In addition, dependant on cost, we may include the family bathroom, kitchen and tiled roof on her current conservatory. Her current flat roofed entrance porch is the subject of an insurance claim, following storm damage.
The whole thing has become a matter of urgency, as my wife and children currently live in private accommodation, which the landlord has apparently decided to sell. We were originally given to the end of January to move out, but he has agreed to allow us to stay until the end of June 2023, to allow the children to complete GCSE's and A Levels. 
We are hoping not to extend the current footprint of the property, as we have a limited budget.

project_detail:
Hi,

We are in a 20 year old, three-storey terraced house with an integrated garage at the front of the property (adjacent to the hallway). Across the back of the property is a kitchen/diner.

We are considering either converting the whole garage and inserting a window in place of the garage door, or converting 2/3rds of the garage and keeping the garage door and a small garage storage space.

We would also be looking to remove the current kitchen, put a new kitchen into the converted garage space and to remove the internal walls to create a larger open plan kitchen/dining/living space.

We would be looking to have the work project managed. We are interested to hear from experienced and professional local tradespeople who might be able to provide advice on how we start this project / how long the project might take / fee quotes.

Many thanks,

Ellie & Tim

project_detail:
We have tenants in one of our rented properties who reported they had a concern about the kitchen floor sinking. Their concern was highlighted because, as you can see, the worktop has dropped about an inch from the wall tiles. The cupboards are also separating at the bottom. 

We thought that there might have been a long standing leak under the sink, so we sent a contractor round to investigate. They took the plinths off, but the floor underneath the cupboards is bone dry. Full of cobwebs etc.

As you can see, the top flooring is ceramic tiles, which we didn’t want to start ripping up unnecessarily. Underneath the units, where the tiles end, we can see that the sub floor that the tiles sit on is plywood. We have to assume at this point that the plywood is overboarded onto floor boards, which sit on joists, but without taking the tiles up we cant be sure. 

We need someone to inspect the timbers (we appreciate that the floor tiles would have to be disturbed somewhere, somehow), and if that identified an issue, we would need someone to undertake the whole task of possibly replacing joists and flooring, and everything incidental that this would entail, ie removal and refitting cupboards, plumbing etc etc.
summary: joinery, kitchen cupboard refitting, flooring / I'm not sure / No - plans are not required / I'm definitely going to hire someone
